{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Block outbound exfiltration to the attacker's C2 server by enforcing host-level network controls on the Ubuntu agent. Specifically, configure iptables to log and drop any TCP traffic destined to 203.0.113.1 on port 8443, and persist the rules for continuity in the digital twin.",
  "comments": "The attacker currently uses the Ubuntu agent (ubuntu_agent_sandcat_https-1) to exfiltrate data to 203.0.113.1:8443. Since we cannot remove the compromised host, we blocked its ability to reach the attacker's C2 port directly. We added two iptables rules on the Ubuntu computer: first to log any attempts to connect to 203.0.113.1:8443, and second to reject those connections with a TCP reset. We then saved/persisted the iptables rules. This approach directly disrupts the exfiltration step (T1041) and data staging transfers (T1074.001) while leaving other network functionality intact. The attack can be validated by re-running the exfiltration attempt; if it still tries, the connection will be blocked and logged, providing observable evidence for SOC and transferable lesson for real networks (focus on egress control at host level when containment cannot rely on host removal).",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "iptables -A OUTPUT -d 203.0.113.1 -p tcp --dport 8443 -j LOG --log-prefix 'C2_DROP:'",
    "iptables -A OUTPUT -d 203.0.113.1 -p tcp --dport 8443 -j REJECT --reject-with tcp-reset",
    "iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4"
  ]
}

{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Migrate host egress filtering from iptables to nftables on the UbuntuComputer to ensure robust, persistent filtering and avoid container limitations; implement a dynamic allow-list for essential outbound destinations and comprehensive logging for validation.",
  "comments": "Implemented nftables-based egress controls on the Ubuntu agent to prevent exfiltration to the attacker's C2 server while preserving normal internal communications. The Ubuntu host now uses an nftables ruleset that blocks outbound traffic to the attacker's IP 203.0.113.1 on port 8443, logs such attempts, and allows typical internal LAN traffic to the FortiGate gateway. This defends against the current exfiltration flow (T1074.001 and T1041) without removing the compromised host, enabling live validation by re-running the attack. The setup provides transferable lessons for real networks: host-based egress filtering with explicit allow/deny rules and audit logging.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "apt-get update -y && apt-get install -y nftables || true",
    "nft -v",
    "printf '%s\n' '#!/usr/sbin/nft -f' > /etc/nftables.conf && printf '%s\n' 'flush ruleset' >> /etc/nftables.conf && printf '%s\n' 'define OUTSIDE = 192.0.2.0/24' >> /etc/nftables.conf && printf '%s\n' 'table inet filter {' >> /etc/nftables.conf && printf '%s\n' '  chain input { type filter hook input priority 0; policy drop; }' >> /etc/nftables.conf && printf '%s\n' '  chain forward { type filter hook forward priority 0; }' >> /etc/nftables.conf && printf '%s\n' '  chain output { type filter hook output priority 0; policy accept; }' >> /etc/nftables.conf && printf '%s\n' '}' >> /etc/nftables.conf",
    "nft -f /etc/nftables.conf",
    "nft list ruleset",
    "cat > /etc/nftables.conf << 'EOF'
#!/usr/sbin/nft -f
flush ruleset

table inet filter {
  chain input {
    type filter hook input priority 0; policy drop;
    iifname "lo" accept
    ct state established,related accept
  }

  chain forward {
    type filter hook forward priority 0; policy accept;
  }

  chain output {
    type filter hook output priority 0; policy accept;
    ip saddr 192.168.1.0/24 accept
    ip daddr 192.168.1.1 accept
    ct state established,related accept
    ip daddr 203.0.113.1 tcp dport 8443 log prefix "C2_DROP: " drop
  }
}
EOF
nft -f /etc/nftables.conf
nft list ruleset",
    "grep -R nõ /proc/sys/net/bridge || true",
    "sysctl -p 2>/dev/null; nft list ruleset; iptables -L -vn; echo DONE"
  ]
}

{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Refined host-based egress controls on the UbuntuComputer by deploying a strict nftables ruleset that allows only traffic to the local gateway (192.168.1.1) and DNS traffic to the gateway, while dropping all other outbound traffic. This creates a robust, persistent path for legitimate internal management while blocking exfiltration attempts to non-authorized destinations. The rule set enforces established/related traffic, blocks direct internet egress except through the FortiGate gateway, and logs activity for validation. This complements the existing inline Snort (which remains untouched) and the attempted NAC deployment (which could not be completed due to template availability).",
  "comments": "The ongoing attack currently exfiltrates via 203.0.113.1:8443. By restricting the Ubuntu host to only reach the FortiGate gateway (192.168.1.1) and local DNS paths, we force all egress to pass through the security perimeter while preventing direct connections to external C2 endpoints. If the attacker attempts alternative channels (other ports, DNS tunneling, or encrypted channels), the host-level firewall will block those, and we can escalate at the network level (NAC/FortiGate) in subsequent steps. The setup provides a transferable blueprint for real environments: explicit allow-list-based egress, persistent nftables configuration, and centralized logging for validation.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "cat > /etc/nftables.conf << 'EOF'
#!/usr/sbin/nft -f
flush ruleset

table inet filter {
  chain input {
    type filter hook input priority 0; policy drop;
    iifname "lo" accept
    ct state established,related accept
  }

  chain forward {
    type filter hook forward priority 0; policy accept;
  }

  chain output {
    type filter hook output priority 0; policy drop;
    # allow internal LAN gateway
    ip daddr 192.168.1.1 accept
    # allow DNS to gateway (DNS resolution via FortiGate)
    udp dport 53 ip daddr 192.168.1.1 accept
    tcp dport 53 ip daddr 192.168.1.1 accept
    # allow loopback
    iifname "lo" accept
    # allow established/related connections
    ct state established,related accept
  }
}
EOF
nft -f /etc/nftables.conf
nft list ruleset"
  ]
}
